IncidentSuppNarrative.NarrativeText: Crash Team Investigation (For review by the MSP Crash Team) NARRATIVE: Vehicle 1: DE XQ362142 Red Chevrolet Sonic Driver:VA Yassin Firas Alallaq (07/22/2002, 5/M) Vehicle 2: MD 68450CF White Subaru Outback Driver: Barbara Dulin South (11/04/1956,2/F) On April 3, 2023 at approximately 0803 hours, the MSP Centreville Barrack responded to the area of Northbound Route 301 and Rolling Bridge Rd located in Queen Annes County, Maryland, for a report of a serious motor vehicle collision. The collision involved a 2012 Chevrolet Sonic and a 2015 Subaru Outback, both vehicles only had a single occupant. The driver of the Outback, Barbara South, was flown to University of MD Shock Trauma by MSP Trooper and the driver of the Sonic, Alallaq, was transported to University of MD Queenstown Emergency Room for minor injuries. South remains in critical condition at Shock Trauma and her status will be monitored. MSP Centreville Troopers on scene requested the assistance of an Advanced Collision Investigator to respond to the crash. I was on duty at MSP Easton Barrack and responded for the ACI. A report documenting my activities will be completed and attached to RMS. ATTACHED SUPPORTING DOCUMENTATION: The following items were attached to this report: None The following digital photographs were taken as part of this investigation and placed into Veri-Pic: None The following items have been archived in the Crash Team Files: None INVESTIGATION STATUS: A report will be authored to document my activities as part of the investigation. This case is open. Authored by: Trooper First Class Christopher Bekefi #7098 MSP Easton Barrack 7053 Ocean Gateway Easton, MD 21601 410-822-3101 text-decoration:underline">Christopher.bekefi@maryland.gov

Detailed Crash Investigation Report (For review by the MSPCrash Team) Agency: Maryland State Police Centreville Scene Recorded on Axon Body Worn Camera Section I. - Introduction: On April 3, 2023 at approximately 0803 hours, Maryland State Police Centreville Barrack responded to the area of Northbound Route 301 in the area of Rolling Bridge Road located in Centreville, Queen Annes county, Maryland for a two-vehicle motor vehicle collision with rollover and injury. Upon TFC Mulhearns arrival on scene, he determined the collision involved the following vehicles and persons. Vehicle #1: 2012 Chevrolet Sonic, DE XQ362142 Registered Owner/ Driver: Alallaq, Yassin Firas (07/22/2002, 5/M) Vehicle #2: 2015 Subaru Outback, MD 68450CF Registered Owner/ Driver: South, Barbara Dulin (11/04/1956, 2/F) Deceased Vehicle 1 was disabled off of the right shoulder in the grass area facing in a northwest direction with heavy front-end damage. Vehicle 2 was disabled on the right shoulder of northbound Route 301 facing in the southbound direction with heavy passenger rear damage as well as roof damage indicating rollover. Queen Anne Deputy Sullivan was first to make contact with South in her vehicle. South suffered a severe head injury and was in and out of consciousness while Deputy Sullivan and Troopers attempted to talk to her. Queen Anne EMS advised that South was alert and speaking with EMS Personnel however became unresponsive prior to transport. Mulhearn made initial contact with Alallaq and advised him he does not remember anything that happened prior to the collision. South was later transported to R Adams Cowley Shock Trauma Center in Baltimore by MSP Trooper 6 for reported life-threatening injuries. The Run Number from Trooper 6 is 23-01093. Alallaq was transported by Queen Annes EMS to UM Shore Emergency Center at Queenstown for minor injuries. The EMS Run Number is 23-001257. Due to the nature of the collision, Mulhearn requested for Maryland State Police CRASH Team to respond to the scene for accident reconstruction. At the time, I was currently on duty at Easton Barrack and responded to the scene for an Advanced Collision Investigation. Upon my arrival, I made contact with TFC Mulhearn and was updated on the status of the investigation. I began to conduct a review of the scene with my Axon Body Worn Camera. I then documented any evidence using digital photography and marked the scene with fluorescent paint. The following report documents my activities as part of this investigation. The scope of this investigation was accomplished by direct investigation or through the findings from other investigative sources. Section II. - Scene Description: (The following descriptions are based on the area where the collision occurred.) Primary Roadway: U.S Route 301 known as Blue Star Memorial Highway is a controlled access highway that travels in a north and south direction. U.S Route 301 has two lanes of travel separated by a white dashed line painted on the roadway. The travel lanes are also supported by a shoulder that are separated from the travel portion by a solid white line painted on the roadway. The roadway was constructed of pressed asphalt material which appeared in good condition with no collision related defects. The speed limit on U.S Route 301 in the area of Rolling Bridge road is 55 Miles Per Hour. Alallaq was traveling in lane 1 (left lane) and South was traveling in lane 2 (right lane) at the time of collision. base64," style="height:284px; margin:5px 10px; width:700px" /> The above image was captured from Google Maps which accurately depicts Northbound Rt. 301 as described above in the area of the collision. base64," style="height:374px; margin:5px 10px; width:700px" /> The Above Image IMG0141 accurately depicts the collision scene on Northbound Route 301 base64," style="height:318px; margin:5px 10px; width:700px" /> The Above Image was captured from the MDOT SHA speed limit map, which accurately depicts the 55 mph posted speed limit on Route 301. The main impact to vehicle 2 occurred on the rear driver side bumper and sustained significant damage. The rear assembly to both lights had been shifted out of place and the right taillight was located in the grass area. The rear windshield had been shattered as a result of the collision. Section VI. - Follow-up Investigation: margin-left: 8px;">Starting on April 3, 2023 I made contact multiple times to Shock Trauma to speak with the Trauma Resuscitation Unit to get an update on Souths condition. I was advised that she was still in Critical Condition for every call I made. margin-left:8px">On April 18, 2023 I was notified by Sgt. Gore South Succumbed to her injuries sustained in the MVC at Shock Trauma. margin-left:8px">On September 13, 2023 I received a copy of Souths Medical Records from Shock Trauma. South sustained a Traumatic Brain Injury caused from the collision, aSpinal Cord fracture in multiple areas including C1 and C4-C6, and traumatic cardiac arrest.From April 3 to April 18 2023, South remained in the multi trauma ICU due to her injuries and ventilator dependent as a result of the collision. On April 18, 2023 at 0921 hours, South was pronounced deceased by Dr. Purtill. The preliminary cause of death was respiratory failure, traumatic brain injury, and high cervical spinal cord injury. All injuries were sustained during the Collison.Autopsy was not completed. Section VII. - Analysis of Electronic Control Modules: See Sgt. Gore Supplement Report. Section VIII. - Speed Analysis: See Sgt. Gore Supplement Report. Section IX. - Crash Dynamics: The following crash dynamics were determined by On Scene Evidence and witness statements. The Subaru Outback was being operated by Barbara Dulin South traveling northbound on Route 301 in lane 2 at approximately 64 mph. The red Chevrolet Sonic was being operated by Yassin Firas Alallaq traveling northbound on Route 301 in lane 1 at approximately 96 mph. Prior to the collision, Alallaq crossed over the white painted dashed line that separates lane 1 from lane 2. The passenger side front of the Chevrolet Sonic struck the driver side rear bumper of the Subaru Outback. This impact caused the back end of the Subaru to kick out and South lost control of the vehicle. The Subaru left the roadway on the right and traveled through the grass area. The Subaru rolled over and completed two or three full rotations before coming to a position of final rest in the shoulder portion on Route 301 on four tires. The Chevrolet Sonic after the collision also left Route 301 on the right and entered the grass area. The vehicle entered a post impact rotation and then traveled up an embankment area. The rear of the vehicle struck a tree on the tree line where I located the rear bumper of the vehicle and observed damage to the tree. After striking the tree, the Sonic came to a position of controlled final rest facing in a northeast direction in the grass. Section X. - Attachments that were included in for this report: The following items were attached to this report: State of Maryland Motor Vehicle CrashReport Alallaq Driver statement Witness Statement 65 On Scene Photographs uploaded to Veri Pic. Conclusion: The following conclusions are based upon the totality of the circumstances including physical evidence observed from the scene, statements made by the witness, and the report submitted by other investigators. On Monday April 3, 2023 at approximately 0803 hours, MSP Centreville barrack received a 911 call for a motor vehicle collision with rollover at Northbound Route 301 in the area of Rolling Bridge Road located in Queen Annes County, Maryland. The Centreville Barrack dispatched TFC J. Mulhearn #6494 to the MVC and QAC Deputy D. Sullivan was first to arrive on scene. Upon their arrival, due to the nature of the collision and the injuries sustained to Barbara South, a request was made for MSP Crash Team to respond to the scene. I, TFC Bekefi #7098, was currently on duty at MSP Easton Barrack and responded to complete an Advanced Collision Investigation at 0812 hours. I arrived on scene at 0853 hours and based on my subsequent investigation the following conclusion has been developed. The White Subaru Outback was being operated by Barbara Dulin South and traveling northbound on Route 301 in lane number 2. The Red Chevrolet Sonic was being operated by Yassin Firas Alallaq and traveling northbound on Route 301 in lane number 1. Alallaq was traveling at a high rate of speed as he approached the Subaru Outback. He then crossed the center dashed line that separates lane 1 from lane 2 and struck the driver side rear of the Outback. The collision at the rate of speed Alallaq was operating his vehicle at caused South to lose control of her vehicle, where she entered a grass area off of the right shoulder. The tire marks observed on scene in the grass show that the front driver side tire reentered the asphalt on the shoulder portion and caused the vehicle to rollover. The Outback rolled approximately 3 times and came to a position of controlled final rest on four tires facing southwest. Alallaq operating the red Chevrolet Sonic after he struck the rear of the Outback also lost control of the vehicle. The vehicle went off the roadway up an embankment and entered into a rotation. The rear of the vehicle struck a tree and came to a postion of controlled final rest. According to the pre-crash data obtained from the vehicle, Alallaq was traveling approximately 96 mph a half second prior to the collision. South was traveling approximately 64 mph a half second prior to the collision. Maryland State Police Trooper 6 transported South to R Adams Cowley Shock Trauma Center in Baltimore due to severe injuries sustained in the collision. These collision events were determined to have been caused by Yassin Firas Alallaq and his wreckless manor while operating the Red Chevrolet Sonic. These Collision events ultimately led to the death of Barbara Dulin South. Upon Approval, this case will be presented to the Queen Annes County States Attorneys Office for criminal charges against Alallaq. TFC C.
